ize=1> Fahrenheit 101 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=neeeeeedra>Neeeeeedra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#333333>(6/13/04 9:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=102>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> !</span><hr size=1> No one can support the &quot;torture&quot; of Iraqi citezens, because the fact is none were tortured.  The people who claim to have been tortured (Which has never been proven in a court of law and by which no one has been proven guilty of doing.) were not merely citezens, but suspects and in many, many cases criminal combatants as witnessed by the U.S. forces who arrested them. Due to being overwhelmed the U.S. forces were too far behind to give each criminal combatant a fair trial according to international law.  Ultimatley, the circumstances surrounding Al Ghraib led to the untimely, and might I add unjustified release of nearly all of the criminal combatants in a political &quot;saving face&quot; effort by the U.S. government.  I trust  each and every soldier who arrested an Iraqi criminal combatant far more than I believe the word of the criminal combatant they arrested.  Like someone said earlier, every person detained in San Quentin is innocent if asked.  To assume the arrested parties are innocent, because they said they were defies logic and takes away from the trust we put into our soldiers, who are, in fact, our brothers, fathers, uncles, aunts, sisters and mothers, and first and foremost Americans.  I understand many of you are not Americans and as far as your opinion goes I understand you have one, but could really give a rats ass really.  You can take your anti American bullshit and stuff it WAY up your ass or if you need help I will supply it.  I don't care what reason you have you should not talk any sort of shit about my country, government, soldiers, citezens, nada, just STFU.  I swear to God if I were face to face with any one of you liberal minded fucked up foreigners and I heard you so much as make any sort of negative comments about what YOU think my country is about I'd smack you in the God damned mouth.  It's not your place to judge us, fuck you, mind your own business and worry about whatever fucked up country you live in and why your countrymen likely sell their sisters to become American citezens and move here.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 1117<br> <font color=#333333>(6/14/04 5:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=103>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: !</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No one can support the &quot;torture&quot; of Iraqi citezens, because the fact is none were tortured<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Hooking people up to electrical wires, raping them, breaking bones and witholding medical treatment for weeks- if that isn't torture then what is?  A little snippet taken from the Taguba report, linked just below:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;5.  (S) That between October and December 2003, at the Abu Ghraib Confinement Facility (BCCF), numerous incidents of sadistic, blatant, and wanton criminal abuses were inflicted on several detainees.  This systemic and illegal abuse of detainees was intentionally perpetrated by several members of the military police guard force (372nd Military Police Company, 320thMilitary Police Battalion, 800th MP Brigade), in Tier (section) 1-A of the Abu Ghraib Prison (BCCF)&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The Geneva Convention relative to the treatment of prisoners of war (GC, RTPOW- 1949) describes torture as &quot;sadistic, blatant and wanton criminal abuse of body and mind&quot;.  Note the striking similarity with Taguba's language- I don't for a moment believe it's a coincidence- not from a senior officer of his experience.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>takes away from the trust we put into our soldiers, who are, in fact, our brothers, fathers, uncles, aunts, sisters and mothers, and first and foremost Americans<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If you trust your soldiers, how about Maj. General Antonio M. Taguba, author of the already cited Taguba report?<br>
<br>
Here is a link to the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.agonist.org/annex/taguba.htm" target="top">Taguba report</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
You said that you don't believe what the detainees said about their treatment, you'd rather put your trust in the American soldier.  Well Taguba disagreed with you.  I draw your attention to Sections 7U, 8U and 9U of the Findings and Recommendations part one.<br>
<br>
Here they are directly cited:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;7.(U) These findings are amply supported by written confessions provided by several of the suspects, written statements provided by detainees, and witness statements.  In reaching my findings, I have carefully considered the pre-existing statements of the following witnesses and suspects&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Five of the suspects who have signed written confessions are then listed.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Confessions</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Neeeedra, you talk about a court of law- I think those confessions might just stand up.  You know something else?  We'll both be around to see it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;8.  (U) In addition, several detainees also described the following acts of abuse, which under the circumstances, I find credible based on the clarity of their statements and supporting evidence provided by other witnesses &quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Eight specific types of abuse are then listed in the report.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;9.  (U) I have carefully considered the statements provided by the following detainees, which under the circumstances I find credible based on the clarity of their statements and supporting evidence provided by other witnesses:&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
All the names of the detainees who made statements are then listed- I've quoted a number of them on page 2 of the thread.  Taguba says he finds the statements credible based on their clarity and supporting evidence.  So if you trust US soldiers discharging their duty, surely you should trust this one also.  Particularly since he's the senior officer in charge of the findings with access to all involved and the pertinent facts.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> (Which has never been proven in a court of law and by which no one has been proven guilty of doing.) were not merely citezens, but suspects and in many, many cases criminal combatants as witnessed by the U.S. forces who arrested them. Due to being overwhelmed the U.S. forces were too far behind to give each criminal combatant a fair trial according to international law<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A question- if these forces are overwhelmed and far behind, why are the US criminal suspects being afforded fair due process when thousands of Iraqi detainees weren't?  You are essentially defending the innocence of soldiers that according to General Taguba's report have signed full and free confessions of wrongdoing.  While at the same time all but assuming guilt of the arrested parties.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Like someone said earlier, every person detained in San Quentin is innocent if asked. To assume the arrested parties are innocent, because they said they were defies logic<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I didn't say they were innocent, their military handlers did.  Yes that's right- read the prisoner classification at the top of the first statement that I quote on page 2 of this thread.  Then cross-reference the name and civilian classification with the Taguba report, linked above.  Those who have read the declassified McKinley reports about the detainees murdered at Bagram airbase know that their classification was &quot;militant/paramilitary&quot;.<br>
<br>
It seems the people who arrested the Iraqi quoted in the first statement *knew* he wasn't guilty of wrongdoing.  Both the Pentagon and the ICRC have said that 80% of the detainees were civilians picked up in random sweeps.  Nowhere will you or anyone else find incontravertible proof that these individuals were &quot;criminal combatants&quot;.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I trust each and every soldier who arrested an Iraqi criminal combatant far more than I believe the word of the criminal combatant they arrested<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
So you'll trust the ones who confessed I take it?  And I assume of course you trust General Taguba's investigation and subsequent report.  Well you must do, he and all his investigative staff are soldiers doing their duty and serving their country.<br>
<br>
Or is it the case that you trust some of the soldiers but not others?  I'm curious about that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I understand many of you are not Americans and as far as your opinion goes I understand you have one, but could really give a rats ass really<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A blatant lie.  If you didn't care you wouldn't have bothered to read past the second page.  If what you said here is true, you wouldn't have written it.  You cared enough to lump everyone who disagrees with you into one category and insult them.  Be obnoxious and petty by all means.  Ignore the facts in good faith.  But don't pretend you &quot;don't give a rat's ass&quot; after saying what you did.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> don't care what reason you have you should not talk any sort of shit about my country, government, soldiers, citezens, nada, just STFU<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I laughed the fuck out loud when I read this.  Why?  Because all of my sources regarding detainee abuse are US military sources.  Practically all of the media sources and criticism quoted came from Americans.  Shit, practically every critical remark of policy I made was paraphrased from statements made by US civil servants or former civil servants, civilian and military.  So I guess if what I said is &quot;talking shit&quot; you should probably gather Colin Powell, Richard Clarke, Anthony Zinni, Antonio Taguba and Norman Schwartzkopf into a room and &quot;smack them in the goddamn mouth&quot;.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It's not your place to judge us, fuck you, mind your own business and worry about whatever fucked up country you live in <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If that's your position, then why did your government order the invasion and occupation of another country?  I suppose they were minding their own business and worrying about whatever fucked up country they lived in!  Turnabout's a bitch when you open mouth without engaging brain first isn't it.<br>
<br>
Not to mention, I'm not judging you or your country.  Your own countrymen are!  Half the US population polled didn't support the policy.  More than half think it's being mismanaged.  Three former CENTCOM commanders (Zinni, Powell, Schwartzkopf) all opposed the invasion.  The White house chief of counterterrorism(Richard Clarke) who served under Reagan, Bush Sr., Clinton and Bush Jr. has said the Iraq war crippled the fight against Al-Qaeda.  They aren't &quot;liberal minded fucked up foreigners&quot; at all.  In fact they all served their country courageously, often putting life and limb on the line for the US.  Which is more incidentally than can be said for Bush, Cheney or Wolfowitz.  <br>
<br>
I'm saying the exact same damn thing as they all have.  In fact, I wouldn't even be thinking the way I do, if they hadn't said it.  So, if you think the ideas expressed are unAmerican- then you'd better come right out of that shell and say Colin Powell, Anthony Zinni, Stormin' Norman, Antonio Taguba, Richard Clarke, Bob Woodward and Kurt Vonnegut Jr. (Mearis' link page 3) are all unAmerican.  If you believe their opinions make them anti-American liberal fucking foreigners, come right out and say it.<br>
<br>
So how if I simply repeat what they've already said- I'm a &quot;liberal minded fucked up foreigner&quot;?  That's something only an intellectually uncurious hypocrite would say.<br>
<br>
