<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>FDR led us into World War II. Germany never attacked us: Japan did. From 1941-1945, 450,000 lives were lost, an average of 112,500 per year. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Germany and Japan are free nations today, something was achieved.  More to the point, the success or failure of a military intervention is not dependent at all upon the number of casualties taken.  It depends upon the success of the war, post-conflict management, exit strategy and the matching of the conflict's pre-war goals (read Klausewitz for god's sake).<br>
<br>
On all of those counts save for victory in the original conflict, the Bush administration has failed miserably.  In Korea, something was achieved, South Korea is a free independent democracy.  Vietnam was mismanaged vis a vis exit strategy.  But it did have clearly designed policy goals and more to the point it had popular support on the ground from the South Vietnamese.  There was a definite border, territory was lost and gained, none of these factors characterize Iraq. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Clinton went to war in Bosnia without UN or French consent. Bosnia never attacked us.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A blatant lie.  I think what you refer to is Kosovo- and even there you had international support under NATO's humanitarian intervention principles.  Bosnia-Herzegovina and the UNIFOR were both staunchly supported by the UN- France had thousands of troops in the original IFOR, in fact they still have over a thousand.  French soldiers fought in Kosovo- people really ought to check their information when forming arguments.<br>
<br>
  In fact the only reason Clinton didn't seek a UN resolution for Kosovo is that Putin asked him not to force a Russian vote of policy conflict.  In other words, Putin supported the intervention but couldn't vote for NATO troops invading a historic Russian ally because it threatened his then-tenuous position.<br>
<br>
Fact is, Clinton *and* Bush Sr. both got international consensus for every single one of their military interventions, all were achieved successfully and an exit strategy with them.  All I might add in the space of less than a year for both Presidents, I very much doubt Iraq will even be close to governable in that time.  <br>
