<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The majority of the american politicians now crying foul during this election year are the same ones that voted FOR regime change in Iraq as a policy<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Show me one sentence in the Congress Iraq war resolution that said regime change.  There isn't one.  I doubt many of the politicians who voted for the resolution realized exactly what it was they were voting for.  Much like the Patriot Act, little formal debate preceded the resolution, and less than half the members of Congress actually read the resolution before its passing.  <br>
<br>
Having said that, I do think it's disgraceful that some politicians have obviously done an about face.  Much like Bush's about face on multilateralism.  Or indeed, the about face on Fallujiah, where a former Saddam general and former Saddam army troops are in charge of security, or in the south where Sistani's militia are being given police uniforms.  <br>
<br>
If one looks carefully, in fact the three regions of Iraq are beginning to split quite clearly along religious and ethnic lines.  Not in terms of demographics, but real political consequence.  Sunni soldiers of Saddam and one of his generals are being given security tasks in the Sunni triangle, Shi'ite militias loyal to the coalition battle with Moqtada al Sadr's militia in the south, and Kurdish peshmergas patrol the northern security zone.  There is little uniting Iraq at the moment, save for a massive presence of foreign troops.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So maybe existent briefcase nukes are more of a threat than non-existent WMDs, I'm sure some would argue that your Intel is as good as the administration had when it made the decision to go into Iraq but isnt that a bit of the pot calling the kettle black?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There is a key difference here, Lehammer hasn't called for military action.  He is simply suggesting that the focus of international pressure and diplomacy should be on the threat of proliferation.  That is, proliferation of KNOWN nuclear stockpiles, that of North Korea, and Pakistan's love affair with selling nuclear material to Iran.  Rather than chasing phantom WMDs via an ill-conceived and incompetently executed occupation strategy, why not simply engage the known stockpiles more forcefully?  The Bush administration has appeased North Korea because of its recently escalated nuclear threat.  Now nations like Iran are rushing towards a nuclear programme because they see nuclear weapons as a road to appeasement and deterrence.  <br>
<br>
The United States adopting a policy of pre-emptive war will encourage proliferation, I said that on this forum before the war.  Iran's belligerence since, and our inability to do anything about it bear out at least some of what I was getting at.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I know this will be received quite comically by the Bush haters out there, but um we are slowly finding evidence of WMD, not stockpiles as of yet, but a shell (confirmed to have) a gallon of Sarin gas (one gallon by the way is capable of killing upwards of 60 thousand people, sounds mass to me)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Hey, I never said I was a Bush hater, merely someone who strongly disagrees with the policies of his administration.  Hey he seems like a fun guy who enjoys a drink or three and throws a good BBQ.  If he invited me I'd go, you get to meet all sorts of interesting people there.  Like say, Tom White, Prince Bandar, and all the Haliburton execs- all kinds of interesting people.<br>
<br>
Saying it has the potential to kill 60,000+ people is as misleading as saying that the flu virus has the potential to wipe out the world's population.  Both statements are true, but are fundamentally misleading scientifically.  Factually speaking it was detonated on a roadside and no one was killed despite being in close proximity.  The CPA also said that the shell was used in isolation, wasn't part of a larger stockpile and those who detonated it almost certainly didn't know what it was.<br>
<br>
Also, the shell derived from an Iran-Iraq war era stockpile, so guess who supplied it to Iraq?  I'll give you 3 guesses :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>in addition to banned Iraqi missle engines that are showing up in neighboring countries<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Those have been around in neighboring nations since pre-Desert Storm days.  So are Iraqi MiGs that were flown into Iran (and summarily captured) and Iraqi towed SSM launchers.  They've been there for over a decade, how are they suddenly evidence of a l33t s33krit WMD programme?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but lets face it, after what 11+ years of violations and the UN not enforcing anything, who in the universe actually thought the UN was going to do anything<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Does anyone else find it ironic that before the war the Bush administration described the UN as a feckless ineffective body, and now the UN is suddenly the last best hope?  Although I am rarely distrustful of UN envoys (heck, the inspectors have been proven right after all)- Lakhdar Brahimi is a very very dodgy character.  As president of the Arab league he supported Saddam as well as Hizbollah's political wing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Do I think the overall outcome is going to be good for the Iraqi people<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I agree it's too early to say about this.  But surely the real question has to be whether the overall outcome was good for the American people.  After all, they are the ones paying for this war, in blood and treasure.  Did the Iraq war make America safer?  All the evidence says no- Lehammer is right, the wrong target is being focused on while terrorists walk free kidnapping, bombing and killing at will.  Afghanistan has been abaondoned, the masterminds are still roaming freely.  <br>
<br>
President Bush has no constitutional duty to &quot;free people around the world&quot; or &quot;respond to a higher father&quot; as he's said.  He does have a responsibility to the American people for their security- and the war didn't serve that security.<br>
<br>
   <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
